collection and surrounding areas only).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35376F1324BFFE7FF66FA9E3965FCE4" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF6257A324BFFE7FF66FA9E39B5FE8B" blockId="4.[151,1436,152,838]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FF66FA9E396FFEA0" bold="true" box="[198,372,232,258]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The species is dedicated to Mr. Alberto 
<collectingCountry id="F35E65EA324BFFE7FCF3FA9E3B84FEA0" box="[851,927,232,258]" name="Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Flores</collectingCountry>
, a farmer from Pucacaca who brought this species to our attention.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF6257A324BFFE7FF66FB433AF4FD95" blockId="4.[151,1436,152,838]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FF66FB433988FEED" bold="true" box="[198,403,309,335]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Observations:—</emphasis>
This new 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FDADFB403A9FFEED" box="[525,644,310,335]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FDADFB403A9FFEED" box="[525,644,310,335]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FC1AFB403C0EFEED" box="[954,1045,310,335]" genus="Pepinia" kingdom="Plantae" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FC1AFB403C0EFEED" box="[954,1045,310,335]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Pepinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Brongniart in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FB74FB433D8FFEED" author="Andre, E." box="[1236,1428,309,335]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" pagination="32 - 33" refId="ref1722" refString="Andre, E. (1870) Pepinia aphelandraeflora. L'Illustration horticole 17: 32 - 33, pl. 5." type="journal article" year="1870">André 1870: 32</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FF37FB2A3976FED4" author="Baker, J. G." box="[151,365,348,374]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" pagination="225 - 233" refId="ref1744" refString="Baker, J. G. (1881) A synopsis of the genus Pitcairnia. Journal of Botany 19: 225 - 233." type="journal article" year="1881">Baker (1881: 227)</bibRefCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FEDCFB2A3A9BFED4" author="Smith, L. B. &amp; Downs, R. J." box="[380,640,348,374]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" refId="ref2126" refString="Smith, L. B. &amp; Downs, R. J. (1974) Pitcairnioideae (Bromeliaceae). In: Flora Neotropica Monograph 14, Part 1. Hafner Press, New York, 660 pp." type="book" year="1974">Smith &amp; Downs 1974</bibRefCitation>
) because the ovules in the ovaries are not appendaged at anthesis. It resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FEBDFBF53B8BFE3E" authority="Linden &amp; Andre (1873: 112)" authorityName="Linden &amp; Andre" authorityPageNumber="112" authorityYear="1873" box="[285,912,386,412]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corallina">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FEBDFBF53A01FE3E" box="[285,538,387,412]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Pitcairnia corallina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FD84FBF43B8BFE3E" author="Linden, J. J. &amp; Andre, E." box="[548,912,386,412]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" pagination="110 - 112" refId="ref1885" refString="Linden, J. J. &amp; Andre, E. (1873) Nouvelles introductions de M. J. Linden - 1873. Annales d'horticulture Belge et etrangere 23: 110 - 112." type="journal article" year="1873">Linden &amp; André (1873: 112)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and has the same tendency to a prostrate inflorescence (strongly curved and short peduncle), but in this case the inflorescence stays well off the ground. The sepals are shorter (
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FE0CFBA63A36FE48" box="[428,557,464,490]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="21.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="19.0">19–23 mm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FDFFFBA63AA9FE48" box="[607,690,464,490]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="26.0">26 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FD7AFBA63B7FFE4B" box="[730,868,464,489]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corallina">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FD7AFBA63B7FFE4B" box="[730,868,464,489]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">P. corallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the petals are yellow and also shorter (
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FAE9FBA63D87FE48" box="[1353,1436,464,490]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="3.3">3.3 cm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FF60FB8138E0FDB3" box="[192,251,503,529]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
long and red with a narrow white margin). The leaf-blades are narrower (
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FBC6FB813CCDFDB3" box="[1126,1238,503,529]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="4.25" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="3.0">3–5.5 cm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity id="4CB1889F324BFFE7FAA8FB813D4AFDB3" box="[1288,1361,503,529]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
wide) and the petiole is entire (vs. serrate in 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FDF5F8683AC6FD95" box="[597,733,542,567]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corallina">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FDF5F8683AC6FD95" box="[597,733,542,567]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">P. corallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF6257A324BFFE7FF66F8323AECFD5B" blockId="4.[151,1436,152,838]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">
It also resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FE39F8323C58FDFC" authority="(Mez 1896: 451) Mez (1935: 270)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="270" authorityYear="1935" baseAuthorityName="Mez" baseAuthorityPageNumber="451" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[409,1091,580,606]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brittoniana">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FE39F8323A85FDFF" box="[409,670,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Pitcairnia brittoniana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FD0FF8323B73FDFC" author="Mez, C." box="[687,872,580,606]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" refId="ref1956" refString="Mez, C. (1896) Bromeliaceae. In: Candolle, A. C. P. de (ed.) Monographiae Phanerogamarum 9. Masson &amp; Cie., Paris, 990 pp." type="book" year="1896">Mez 1896: 451</bibRefCitation>
) Mez (1935: 270)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FB21F8323972FD26" authority="Mez (1904: 628)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="628" authorityYear="1904" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Pitcairnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sceptriformis">
<emphasis id="B93DF968324BFFE7FB21F8323D80FDFF" box="[1153,1435,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Pitcairnia sceptriformis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FF37F81C3972FD26" author="Mez, C." box="[151,361,618,644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" pagination="619 - 634" refId="ref1994" refString="Mez, C. (1904) Additamenta monographica 1904 (part 1). Bulletin de l'Herbier Boissier, series 2, 4: 619 - 634." type="journal article" year="1904">Mez (1904: 628)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in inflorescence (depicted in the nicely illustrated book 
<taxonomicName id="4C495EF9324BFFE7FB96F81C3CFBFD26" box="[1078,1248,618,644]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry id="F35E65EA324BFFE7FAADF81C3D6FFD26" box="[1293,1396,618,644]" name="Ecuador" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8588B324BFFE7FF37F8E73998FD09" author="Manzanares, J. M." box="[151,387,657,683]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33" pagination="241 - 544" refId="ref1921" refString="Manzanares, J. M. (2005) Bromeliaceae of Ecuador (Jewels of the Jungle): Pitcairnioideae. Part 2. Imprenta Mariscal, Quito, pp. 241 - 544." type="book chapter" year="2005">Manzanares (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, but this new species is stemless (vs.long caulescent in other two species). It is totally spineless (vs. at least in some parts with spines on the leaf margins in the other species). The peduncle is short and mostly strongly curved (vs. erect and elongate).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF6257A324BFFE7FF66F9733965FCE4" blockId="4.[151,1436,152,838]" pageId="4" pageNumber="33">
The rhizomes of 
